er and Leopold Jessner, Hegelian speculative dialectics, and the critical philosophy of Jacques Rancière and Slavoj Žižek in order to explore the thinking of Regie – how to think Regie, and how Regie thinks. This partial and ‘sideways look’ invites a wider reconsideration of the potential of ‘playing’ theatre today, of its aesthetic possibilities, and its political stakes in the global neoliberal economy of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTheaterxProduction and directionxHistoryzEurope. 0aTheaterxProduction and directionzEuropexHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh  aFriedrich Schiller.  aGeorg Hegel.  aLeopold Jessner.  aSlavoj Žižek.  aaesthetic politics.  acontemporary Regie.  adirectors' theatre.  aintermedial parallax.  aplay-performance.  asemiocapitalism.  aspeculative thinking.  atheatral appearing.  atruthfulness.1 aBoenisch, Peter M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499172240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784991722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784991722/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles